article.description: Ivory Latta had a game-high 28 points and eight assists and Erlana Larkins added 22 points to lead North Carolina (No. 7 EPSN/USA Today, No. 5 AP) past UNLV 84-76 in the title game of the Lady Rebel Shootout.
article.headline: Tar Heels' Latta, Larkins combine for 50 points
article.linkText: Rebel yell: UNC wins Lady Rebel Shootout title
article.story:
LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Ivory Latta made sure North Carolina's early double-digit lead stood up.

The sophomore point guard had 28 points and seven assists as the Tar Heels (No. 7 EPSN/USA Today, No. 5 AP) outlasted UNLV for an 84-76 victory in the title game of the Lady Rebel Shootout.

North Carolina (5-0) charged to an 18-point lead, and Latta thwarted the Rebels' comeback attempt by going 4-of-4 from the foul line in the closing minutes.

Latta finished 10-of-11 from the line and took home the tournament's most valuable player honors. Teammate Leah Metcalf added 10 points and six assists to earn a spot on the all-tournament team.

"She's just a pest out there," North Carolina coach Sylvia Hatchell said of Latta. "That's a pretty tough kid. We actually moved her to the wing to try to free her up for more shots."

North Carolina shot 20-of-23 as a team from the free-throw line.

Sheena Moore led the Rebels with 25 points, while RanDee Henry had 19 points and nine rebounds.

North Carolina (5-0) never trailed after the opening minutes and hit 12 of its first 18 shots to take a 31-13 lead midway through the first half. The Tar Heels forced nine turnovers during the outburst and scored 22 points off turnovers before halftime.

UNLV (2-3) answered with a 15-2 run, cutting the deficit to 33-28 with about six minutes to play in the half. The Rebels capitalized on a North Carolina technical, hitting two foul shots after the Tar Heels were whistled for having six players on the court following a timeout.

"UNLV is a really great team and they have a lot of weapons," Latta said.

The Rebels never had an answer for Latta, though, who made 7-of-14 shots and came within two points of her career high. She scored 30 against Wake Forest on Jan. 2 in her first ACC game.
